Bubb #133
>>Ein Video mit dem Haller Bürgermeister zu einer anscheinend neuen Entwicklung.
[https://www.t-online.de/tv/news/panorama/id_8...](https://www.t-online.de/tv/news/panorama/id_89761536/-virus-trickst-uns-aus-alarmierender-bericht-aus-klinik-in-halle.html)
BenC #136
>>Es geht darum, dass in einer oder mehreren Kliniken in Halle Personen, die zweimal geimpft worden seien und - zum Glück - völlig symptomfrei in der Klinik (aus anderen Gründen?) erschienen sind, mit einem Schnelltest negativ und dann mit einem PCR-Test positiv getestet wurden. Und das wohl mit einer (sehr) hohen Viruslast.
In-teresting. I searched for any hint of that news item in English, but have come up empty so far. If anyone sees it, please speak up. Or alternatively, should we drop a hint to one of the big wire services? Reuters, AP, anyone up at night?
DW does have one similar report (so far only in English?), about an outbreak of post-vaccination positive tests among 14 nursing-home residents in Osnabruck, as opposed to the 1 man so far in Halle (IIRC). I trust the authorities will follow that up to verify that they really did get both doses, and it really was the Pfizer vaccine, correctly stored at ultracold temps, etc. (And I trust it wasn't an April fool ...)
(The NY Times, in contrast, is evidently well behind the curve on this issue, reporting only that people could hypothetically get infected and spread the virus despite being fully vaccinated. And the Guardian only has a report from Australia about likely aerosol transmission in a hospital ward.)
Surely all of us who have been paying attention were well aware that this could happen in theory. After all, if a vaccine is 90% effective, it's 10% ineffective, right? But since a lot of people seem to have forgotten, or not thought about it, it seems crucial to me to report the real-life stories now, just so that people don't get complacent about masks, ventilation, and distancing, vaccinated or not.
That said, we went ahead and hosted two different fully vaccinated couples for indoor meals this week, Sunday noon and Monday night, without masks. So I hope that wasn't a dumb thing to do. The chances still seem generally pretty good that the vaccine will prevent infection, for any individual person who's not already frail or immunocompromised.
That might explain why the vaccine was less protective for nursing-home residents, who might be expected to have a weaker immune response to the vaccine. But even there, at least none of them have gotten sick so far, knock wood.
I wonder if virologists will now recommend perhaps a 3rd booster shot for people in the oldest, highest-risk categories. Or if, as I suspect, we can't afford to do that yet any time soon, so we need to first get more nursing-home staff and visitors, and the rest of society, vaccinated.
Anyway, I hope journalists worldwide aren't dropping the ball completely on this angle, just because the first stories of people infected after vaccination seem to be breaking on a holiday weekend. /-:
________________________
Doppelt geimpft und trotzdem positiv getestet! Wie kann sowas sein?
Corona-Schnelltest war negativ
Dieser Corona-Fall ist mysteriös: In einer Klinik in Halle wurde ein Mann positiv auf das Coronavirus getestet – und das, obwohl er bereits die doppelte Impfung erhalten hatte, negativ getestet war und keine Symptome aufwies. Erst bei einem PCR-Test kam heraus: Der Mann hat trotzdem eine hohe Viruslast! Wie kann sowas sein?
Offenbar ist es dem Coronavirus also gelungen, auch vollständig geimpfte Menschen so zu befallen, dass das Virus in hoher Zahl in Mund- und Rachenraum nachgewiesen werden kann. "Aber, es ist dem Virus nicht gelungen, diese Person krank zu machen. Sie erfreut sich bester Gesundheit", so der Klinikdirektor des St. Elisabeth Krankenhauses Dr. Hendrik Liedtke. Ob der Mann in der Klinik noch weitere Menschen angesteckt hat, wird derzeit noch geprüft. ...
Aber wie kann das sein? Ungewöhnlicher Fall oder doch möglich? Dr. Georg-Christian Zinn, Direktor Hygienezentrum Bioscientia, ist nicht überrascht. "Das kann in seltenen Fällen vorkommen. Bei anderen Impfungen, wie zum Beispiel gegen Hepatitis B, haben wir sogenannte Non-Responder. Das sind Menschen, die nicht auf die Impfung reagieren und tatsächlich auch erkranken können." Diese Menschen bilden also nach der Impfung keine oder nur sehr wenige Antikörper. Dr. Zinn hält diese These in dem Fall aus Halle für sehr wahrscheinlich. "Diese seltenen Einzelfälle kann es eben geben."

Coronavirus digest: German nursing home sees outbreak after vaccines
Fourteen residents at a German nursing home have tested positive despite receiving two vaccine doses. Markus Söder has warned against lifting Germany's lockdown too soon. All the latest COVID news. ...
Local officials in the district of Osnabruck, Germany, said there was an outbreak of the UK variant of coronavirus at a nursing home in Belm.
The outbreak came despite all of its residents already receiving two doses of the BioNTech-Pfizer vaccine, with their last shot on January 25.
A local goverment spokesperson said 14 residents tested positive for the virus at the end of last week.
None of them showed any serious symptoms associated with COVID-19. It is unclear exactly how and when the residents became infected, officials said.

Can Vaccinated People Spread the Virus? We Don’t Know, Scientists Say.
Researchers pushed back after the C.D.C. director asserted that vaccinated people “do not carry the virus.” ...
The Centers for Disease Control and Prevention on Thursday walked back controversial comments made by its director, Dr. Rochelle P. Walensky, suggesting that people who are vaccinated against the coronavirus never become infected or transmit the virus to others. ...
The data suggest that “it’s much harder for vaccinated people to get infected, but don’t think for one second that they cannot get infected,” said Paul Duprex, director of the Center for Vaccine Research at the University of Pittsburgh.

Was it airborne? Queensland's Covid outbreak and mystery of hospital ward 5D
The second and third Brisbane cases were two Princess Alexandra nurses who did not come into contact with the patient they caught Covid from ...
Late on Wednesday, all hospital staff members who entered the infectious diseases ward from Tuesday to Friday last week – whether or not they came into contact with patients – were ordered into quarantine.
The ward is central to understanding how UK-variant coronavirus cases entered and subsequently spread in the Brisbane community, prompting a three-day citywide lockdown and restrictions in two states.

My Patients Need Treatment for Covid-19. Why Can’t They Get It?
Doctors like me want monoclonal antibodies for our high-risk patients, but the medicine is hard to come by. ...
Monoclonal antibodies are made in the laboratory and are designed to mimic the immune system’s ability to fight off invaders like viruses. ... They have been found effective in treating people at a high risk of complications from Covid-19, and last fall the Food and Drug Administration approved their emergency use to treat the disease. But right now it’s too hard for patients to obtain this treatment. ...
As a clinical hematologist caring for people with compromised immune systems, I have watched in horror as Covid-19 has ravaged my patients. ... Despite progress in vaccinations, the coronavirus remains a persistent and even growing problem in New York City, where about 4,000 new cases of Covid-19 are being identified every day and thousands of people remain hospitalized.
When President Donald Trump fell sick with Covid-19 in October, he received monoclonal antibodies, as did several senior membersof his inner circle. All of them survived, as do nearly 90 percent of high-risk patients who are treated early with this medication. ...
A colleague and I recently called every hospital in New York City’s five boroughs to find out whether they offer monoclonal antibodies to high-risk patients with Covid-19. Only three said they could provide the therapy to a high-risk patient without symptoms. ...
The Biden administration has pledged to make monoclonal antibody treatment more available, with a $150 million plan to deliver it to more patients who need it. This is a welcome development, but so far, in the field, we have seen no tangible change in access to treatment.
Perry Cook is a hematologist and oncologist at NewYork-Presbyterian Brooklyn Methodist Hospital and Weill Cornell Medicine in New York City.
[https://www.nytimes.com/2021/03/31/opinion/co...](https://www.nytimes.com/2021/03/31/opinion/covid-monoclonal-antibodies-treatment.html)
Factory Mix-Up Ruins Up to 15 Million Vaccine Doses From Johnson & Johnson
A manufacturing subcontractor in Baltimore mixed ingredients from the coronavirus vaccines of Johnson & Johnson and AstraZeneca, delaying U.S. shipments of the “one-and-done” shot. ...
The plant is run by Emergent BioSolutions, a manufacturing partner to both Johnson & Johnson and AstraZeneca, the British-Swedish company whose vaccine has yet to be authorized for use in the United States. Federal officials attributed the mistake to human error.
The mix-up has delayed future shipments of Johnson & Johnson doses in the United States while the Food and Drug Administration investigates what occurred. Johnson & Johnson has moved to strengthen its control over Emergent BioSolutions’ work to avoid additional quality lapses.
The mistake is a major embarrassment both for Johnson & Johnson, whose one-dose vaccine has been credited with speeding up the national immunization program, and for Emergent, its subcontractor, which has faced fierce criticism for its heavy lobbying for federal contracts,
(
